07/04/2023, 18:22 - Mathieu Ract: CAN you answer this question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok : An analysis of the problem currently, addressed by the startup and
"potential" of the problem (growing? Frequent? Painful?)
Yes, I can certainly help you with your question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok.

Yindii is a startup that aims to reduce food waste and support sustainable consumption by connecting users with discounted surplus food from restaurants and cafes in Bangkok. The problem that Yindii addresses is the issue of food waste, which is a growing concern not just in Thailand but worldwide. According to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), roughly one-third of all food produced for human consumption is lost or wasted globally, which amounts to about 1.3 billion tons of food per year.

In Thailand, the problem of food waste is also significant, with the country generating over 21.4 million tons of food waste each year, according to a report by the Thai Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment. This waste has environmental, economic, and social impacts, including increased greenhouse gas emissions, wasted resources, and missed opportunities to provide food to those in need.

Yindii addresses this problem by providing a platform for restaurants and cafes to sell their surplus food at discounted prices to users who can purchase it through the Yindii app. This helps to reduce the amount of food that goes to waste while also providing an affordable option for users who may not be able to afford full-priced meals.

The potential for the problem of food waste is significant and growing, as the population continues to increase, and consumption patterns change. With more people living in cities and demanding convenience, food waste from restaurants and cafes is likely to continue to be a frequent and painful problem in the future.

Overall, Yindii has identified a pressing and urgent problem in Thailand and is taking innovative steps to address it through their platform. By doing so, they are not only helping to reduce food waste but also promoting sustainable consumption practices and helping to make food more affordable and accessible to a wider range of people.

CAN you answer this question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok : An analysis of the solution currently offered by the startup: what is its
value proposition, how efficient is it compared to alternative solutions,
could it be improved
Yes, I can certainly help you with your question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok.

Yindii's value proposition is to provide an affordable and convenient solution for both users and restaurants to reduce food waste. Through their platform, Yindii allows users to purchase surplus food from restaurants and cafes at a discounted price, providing a win-win situation for both parties. Users benefit from affordable meals, while restaurants benefit from reducing food waste and generating additional revenue.

Compared to alternative solutions, Yindii's approach is efficient and innovative. Traditional methods for reducing food waste involve donating excess food to food banks or composting, which can be time-consuming and costly for restaurants. Yindii's platform streamlines the process and makes it easier for restaurants to sell their surplus food quickly and efficiently.

In addition, Yindii's approach also promotes sustainability by reducing the amount of food that ends up in landfills, which helps to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and preserve natural resources. This approach aligns with the increasing consumer demand for sustainable and eco-friendly solutions.

However, there are potential areas for improvement. One challenge that Yindii may face is the availability of surplus food from restaurants and cafes. Yindii relies on restaurants and cafes to have excess food to sell on their platform, which can be unpredictable and inconsistent. In addition, Yindii's platform currently only operates in Bangkok, limiting its potential impact.

Another potential challenge is the risk of food safety issues. Yindii works closely with restaurants and cafes to ensure that the food sold on their platform is safe and of good quality. However, there is still a risk of foodborne illness, which could damage the reputation of Yindii and its partner restaurants.

Overall, Yindii's solution offers a valuable and innovative approach to reducing food waste in Bangkok. While there are potential areas for improvement, Yindii has identified a pressing issue and is taking meaningful steps to address it in a way that benefits both users and restaurants.




Mathieu Ract
CAN you answer this question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok : An analysis of the problem validation and solution iteration journey
that brought the founder to the current problem and solution
Yes, I can certainly help you with your question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok.

Yindii's founder, Karin Lindell, was inspired to start the company after seeing firsthand the amount of food waste generated by the restaurant industry in Bangkok. She noticed that restaurants were throwing away large amounts of perfectly good food at the end of each day, which not only had a negative impact on the environment but was also a missed opportunity to provide food to people in need.

To validate the problem, Lindell conducted extensive research and spoke with restaurant owners and managers in Bangkok. She found that food waste was a significant issue for the industry, and many restaurant owners were looking for ways to reduce their waste and improve their environmental impact.

Based on this research, Lindell developed the idea for Yindii, a platform that would allow restaurants and cafes to sell their surplus food to users at a discounted price. She believed that this approach would not only help to reduce food waste but would also provide a solution for consumers looking for affordable meals.

To validate the solution, Lindell launched a pilot program in Bangkok in 2019, working with a small group of restaurants and cafes to test the platform. The pilot was successful, with positive feedback from both users and participating restaurants. Based on this feedback, Lindell continued to iterate and improve the platform, adding new features and expanding the number of restaurants and cafes on the platform.

Over time, Yindii has continued to refine and improve its platform, based on feedback from users and partner restaurants. The company has also expanded its impact, partnering with food banks and other organizations to donate surplus food that cannot be sold on the platform.

Overall, Yindii's problem validation and solution iteration journey is an example of how startups can develop innovative solutions to pressing social and environmental issues. By conducting extensive research and testing, Yindii was able to identify a significant problem and develop a solution that benefits both restaurants and consumers. Through ongoing iteration and improvement, Yindii has continued to grow and expand its impact, helping to reduce food waste and promote sustainable consumption in Bangkok.




Mathieu Ract
CAN you answer this question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok : An analysis of one major strategic challenge the startup currently
faces including 2 or 3 possible options of solving it and your justified
recommended option
Yes, I can certainly help you with your question about the startup Yindii in Bangkok.

One major strategic challenge that Yindii currently faces is the availability of surplus food from restaurants and cafes. Yindii relies on restaurants and cafes to have excess food to sell on their platform, which can be unpredictable and inconsistent. This creates a challenge for Yindii, as the platform's success depends on the availability of surplus food.

To address this challenge, Yindii has several options:

Expand the number of partner restaurants and cafes: One option is for Yindii to expand its network of partner restaurants and cafes. By increasing the number of partners, Yindii can increase the likelihood of having surplus food available on its platform. This could involve reaching out to more restaurants and cafes, offering incentives to join the platform, or expanding into new geographic areas.

Work with restaurants to reduce food waste: Another option is for Yindii to work with its partner restaurants and cafes to reduce food waste. By helping restaurants to manage their inventory and reduce food waste, Yindii can increase the availability of surplus food on its platform. This could involve providing training and support to restaurants on food waste reduction techniques, or working with restaurants to improve their supply chain management.

Develop a new product or service: Yindii could also consider developing a new product or service that is less dependent on the availability of surplus food. For example, Yindii could launch a meal delivery service or offer catering services that are focused on reducing food waste. This would allow Yindii to expand its offerings beyond surplus food and increase its revenue streams.

My recommended option would be to expand the number of partner restaurants and cafes. While working with restaurants to reduce food waste is important, it may not be enough to ensure a consistent supply of surplus food for Yindii's platform. By expanding its network of partner restaurants and cafes, Yindii can increase the availability of surplus food and ensure that users have a wide variety of options to choose from. This approach would require a focused effort on outreach and relationship building with potential partners, but it has the potential to provide a sustainable solution to Yindii's current strategic challenge.

22/05/2023, 17:02 - Mathieu Ract: Dear students, 

 

Welcome to the course "Managing IT in the Digital Age" in May and June 2023. We are trying out an innovative way of pedagogy this year which will allow you to learn this course at your own pace. You do not need to come to the classroom as scheduled except for 3 sessions. You can learn it whenever and wherever you are. Delivery of all other courses remains the same. 

 

All the course materials (videos of lectures, slides, readings, group projects and an individual assignment) for "Managing IT in the Digital Age" have been provided on the course website. Please go through the slides or video of Session 1 to understand the course structure and requirements.  In order to do your group project, you need to finish reading a book first. On the course website, in the folder about Group presentations, you can find the information about how to access the ebook at ESSEC Learning Center. We also have some hardcopies of the book in our Learning Center on the 4th floor. But we don't have 100 copies, so first come, first served. You can also find your group member information in the Excel file in that folder. Please come to class for the following sessions:

 

Group A

June 8th am group presentation by team 1-4 in classroom

June 13th am group presentation by team 5-7 and Q&A session for the course in classroom

 

Group B

June 8th pm group presentation by team 1-4 in classroom

June 13th pm group presentation by team 5-7 and Q&A session for the course in classroom

 

Final Exam

June 21st am in classroom

 

Please feel free to email Professor Li whenever you have any questions about the course.

- Points overall: 45. Hence, the exam is designed for achieving 45 points in 45 minutes so that the number of points gives you an indication for the amount of time you should invest into each answer
